  <p class="article-lede">Ghana's agro-processing sector has been GhanaWorld's top-ranked opportunity for 40 consecutive cycles. At 8.5 out of 10, it outscores every other sector in the economy. The thesis is not complicated: Ghana grows far more than it processes, and the gap between raw material and finished product is where disciplined operators make money. What is new in 2026 is the convergence of three forces that compress the opportunity into a specific window: the IMF exit timeline, the cocoa crisis pushing capital toward non-cocoa crops, and GHS 1.7 billion (approximately $155 million) in government infrastructure investment flowing into processing zones.</p>

  <p>That window opens now and closes in approximately 12 months. This article explains why, maps the four strongest sub-sectors, names every major constraint that kills processors, and provides the honest unit economics that will determine whether your specific operation survives.</p>

  <h2 id="thesis-in-numbers">The Thesis in Numbers</h2>

  <div class="data-box">
    <h4>Ghana Agro-Processing: Key Indicators</h4>
    <table>
      <tr><th>Indicator</th><th>Value</th><th>Source</th></tr>
      <tr><td>GhanaWorld Sector Score</td><td>8.5 / 10.0 (#1 ranked)</td><td>GhanaWorld Sector Rankings, 40 cycles</td></tr>
