  </div>

  <p>A 26.7% gross margin sounds adequate but leaves thin room for error. A 15% increase in cassava input prices (seasonal price spike or transport cost increase) compresses the margin to approximately 18%. A simultaneous diesel price increase (as currently occurring due to Hormuz) compresses further. This is why FP-006 (thin working capital) is lethal: there is no margin buffer to absorb unexpected cost increases without reserves.</p>

  <p>Shea butter for export operates at higher gross margins (40 to 60% for certified cosmetic-grade product), but with higher upfront investment in certification, quality testing equipment, and longer cash conversion cycles due to export payment terms (typically 60 to 90 days).</p>

  <h2 id="hormuz-overlay">The Hormuz Overlay</h2>

  <p>The Strait of Hormuz crisis (detailed in our <a href="/analysis/hormuz-crisis-ghana-2026">Hormuz transmission analysis</a>) has increased diesel prices by 25.7% in a single NPA pricing window. For agro-processors, this affects three cost lines: generator fuel, transport (farm to factory and factory to market), and the expectation-driven repricing of locally sourced inputs.</p>

  <p>GhanaWorld's sector-by-sector assessment rates agro-processing diesel dependency as HIGH, with a margin impact of negative 5 to 8%. This is survivable for well-capitalized operators but potentially fatal for underfunded processors already operating at thin margins.</p>

  <p>The recommended stress test: rerun all unit economics at GHS 18 per liter diesel (the projected price if Brent stays above $110 through the April NPA pricing window). If your model remains viable at GHS 18 diesel, you have adequate margin. If it breaks, you need either higher output prices, lower input costs, or a solar-hybrid power system that reduces generator dependency by at least 40%.</p>

